collisionQueryRange.title: Collision Query Range
collisionQueryRange.description: Defines how close a collision element must be before it is considered for steering behaviors. [Limits: > 0]

separationWeight.title: Separation Weight
separationWeight.description: How aggressive the agent manager should be at avoiding collisions with this agent. [Limit: >= 0]

stopDistance.title: Stop Distance
stopDistance.description: The distance from the path end point this agent should stop at. If 0.0 is provided the agent will reach as close as possible to the end point.

orientInertia.title: Orient Inertia
orientInertia.description: How smoothly the agent entity will rotate to orient itself.

orientAgent.title: Orient Agent
orientAgent.description: If selected the agent entity will automatically orient itself on the Y axis to look at the next point on the path.

pathfinderEntity.title: Pathfinder
pathfinderEntity.description: Drag and drop the pathfinder entity this obstacle should interact with. Updating this requires regenerating the navmesh or reloading your app

obstacleType.title: Obstacle Type
obstacleType.description: Set the type of the obstacle shape.

boxExtents.title: Box Extents
boxExtents.description: The box extents on each axis.

boxYAngle.title: Box Y Angle
boxYAngle.description: The angle of the box orientation on the Y axis.

initialState.title: Initial State
initialState.description: If the obstacle will be enabled or disabled when the navmesh is generated.

pathfinderEntity.title: Pathfinder
pathfinderEntity.description: Drag and drop the pathfinder entity this crowd should interact with. Updating this requires regenerating the navmesh or reloading your app

maxAgents.title: Max Agents
maxAgents.description: The maximum number of agents allowed on this crowd.

maxAgentRadius.title: Max Agent Radius
maxAgentRadius.description: The maximum radius an agent can have.

cellSize.title: Cell Size
cellSize.description: XZ plane cell size, used to calculate the grid size based on the bounding box of the selected scene. [Limit: >= 0]

cellHeight.title: Cell Height
cellHeight.description: Y-axis cell size, used to calculate the grid size based on the bounding box of the selected scene. [Limit: >= 0]

walkableHeight.title: Walkable Height
walkableHeight.description: Minimum floor to ceiling height that will still allow the floor area to be considered walkable. [Limit: >=0]

walkableRadius.title: Walkable Radius
walkableRadius.description: The distance to erode/shrink the walkable area of the heightfield away from obstructions. [Limit: >=0]

walkableClimb.title: Walkable Climb
walkableClimb.description: Maximum ledge height that is considered to still be traversable. [Limit: >=0]

regionMinSize.title: Region Min Size
regionMinSize.description: The minimum number of cells allowed to form isolated island areas. [Limit: >=0]

regionMergeSize.title: Region Merge Size
regionMergeSize.description: Any regions with a span count smaller than this value will, if possible, be merged with larger regions. [Limit: >=0]

edgeMaxLen.title: Edge Max Length
edgeMaxLen.description: The maximum allowed length for contour edges along the border of the mesh. [Limit: >=0]

edgeMaxError.title: Edge Max Error
edgeMaxError.description: The maximum distance a simplfied contour's border edges should deviate the original raw contour. [Limit: >=0]

vertsPerPoly.title: Max Verts Per Poly
vertsPerPoly.description: The maximum number of vertices allowed for polygons generated during the contour to polygon conversion process. [Limit: >= 3]

detailSampleDist.title: Detail Sample Dist
detailSampleDist.description: Sets the sampling distance to use when generating the detail mesh, for height detail only. [Limits: >= 0.9]

detailSampleMaxError.title: Detail Sample Max Error
detailSampleMaxError.description: The maximum distance the detail mesh surface should deviate from heightfield data, for height detail only. [Limit: >=0]

tileSize.title: Tile Size
tileSize.description: The width/height size of tile's on the xz-plane. If you plan to use obstacles the tileSize should be > 0. [Limit: >= 0]

borderSize.title: Border Size
borderSize.description: The size of the non-navigable border around the heightfield. [Limit: >= 0]

debugNavMesh.title: Debug Nav Mesh
debugNavMesh.description: If enabled the generated nav mesh will be rendered.

queryExtent.title: Query Extent
queryExtent.description: Set the Bounding box extent for doing spatial queries (getClosestPoint, getRandomPointAround etc.).

excludeTags.title: Exclude Tags
excludeTags.description: A comma separated list of entity tags to exclude from the navmesh.

onEventStart.title: On Event Start
onEventStart.description: Run the navmesh generator when this app wide event fires, if empty the navmesh will be generated on initialize.

onEventReady.title: On Event Ready
onEventReady.description: Fire a custom event when the navmesh generation finished.

pan.title: Pan
pan.description: Before the cinema camera activates, you can either immediately teleport game camera to it, or have a gradual transition (pan) to it.

panDuration.title: Pan Duration
panDuration.description: If pan is enabled, this number will specify how long the panning will take in seconds.

lerp.title: Lerp
lerp.description: If non-zero, the game camera will smoothly chase the cinema camera, technically never reaching it, always getting closer. The smaller the number, the faster it will close the distance between them.

localUp.title: Use Local UP
localUp.description: If checked, uses cinema camera local UP vector, instead of world UP. Enable this, if you need to look directly up or down.

projDuration.title: Projection Blend Duration
projDuration.description: When a cinema camera is activated with a different projection type (e.g. perspective vs orthographic), this will specify how long the blending will be in seconds.

overrideLayers.title: Override Layers
overrideLayers.description: If enabled, will use the layers that are listed in this cinema camera.

assetTag.title: Asset Tag
assetTag.description: A tag used on a list of assets to be loaded/unloaded automatically by this script.

defaultTweenUpdate.title: Default Tween Update
defaultTweenUpdate.description: If unchecked, you will need to manually fire("MOTOR:onTween", dt) when you want your tweens to update.This is useful, for example, if you want APP.tween to update in a "post update" method, instead of the default "update".

schema.name: masks
schema.title: Masks
schema.description: Bone this layer will affect. (This will override the File Masks property if set)

curvePower.title: Curve Power
curvePower.description: Determines the amount of curviness to be applied.

curveDirection.title: Curve Direction
curveDirection.description: This is a normalized factor that sets the curve direction from 0 to 1 on each axis.

activeCamera.title: Active Camera
activeCamera.description: An optional active camera can be passed to calculate the effect in relation to the camera world position. If no camera is passed the effect will be calculated from 0,0,0.

onEventBoot.title: On Event Boot
onEventBoot.description: If an event name is provided then the effect will be initialized after that event is fired.

onEventDestroy.title: On Event Destroy
onEventDestroy.description: If an event name is provided then the effect will be destroyed after that event is fired.

orient.title: Face Camera
orient.description: Vertices are positioned so that they always face the camera.

motionThreshold.title: Motion Threshold
motionThreshold.description: Number of meters moved in one frame before CCD is enabled

sweptSphereRadius.title: Swept Sphere Radius
sweptSphereRadius.description: This should be below the half extent of the collision volume. E.g For an object of dimensions 1 meter, try 0.2

centerOfMass.title: Center Of Mass
centerOfMass.description: The initial center-of-mass of the rigid-body to create.

dominanceGroup.title: Dominance Group
dominanceGroup.description: Each rigid-body is part of a dominance group in [-127; 127] (the default group is 0). If the colliders from two rigid-bodies are in contact, the one with the highest dominance will act as if it has an infinite mass, making it immune to the contact forces the other body would apply on it. If both bodies are part of the same dominance group, then their contacts will work in the usual way (both are affected by opposite forces with the same magnitude).For example, if a dynamic body A is in the dominance group 10, and a dynamic body B in the dominance group -20, then a contact between a collider attached to A and a collider attached B will result in A remaining immobile and B being pushed by A (independently from their mass).

gravityScale.title: Gravity Scale
gravityScale.description: Scales the gravity affecting this particular rigidbody. Setting it to 0, means it will no longer be affected by gravity.

collisionFilter.title: Collision Filter
collisionFilter.description: Specifies collision filtering groups. This filter is applied before contacts calculation in narrow phase. You normally want to use this one.

schema.name: membership
schema.title: Membership
schema.description: Groups that this collider belong to. If none specified, a collider will be assigned to a default group "DEFAULT".

schema.name: filter
schema.title: Filter
schema.description: Groups that this collider can interact with. If none specified, a default group "DEFAULT" will be set.

schema.name: invert
schema.title: Invert
schema.description: Inverts the filter, so this collider will interact with all colliders that are part of "DEFAULT", except those groups that are listed in the filter.

density.title: Density
density.description: Physics engine will automatically calculate the mass of the collider based its shape and density.

mass.title: Mass
mass.description: Keep it -1 to let the physics engine to automatically calculate the mass of the collider, based on its shape and density. Use 0 or more to override automatic calculation.

contactForceThreshold.title: Contact Force Threshold
contactForceThreshold.description: Sets a minimum threshold of a contact force magnitude between two bodies. Contact events below this threshold will be ignored. Useful, when you want to ignore some light collisions. Defaults to zero (all collision events reported). The threshold will depend on the collider shape and size. For a 1m^3 box you could try starting somewhere at 500-1000 and tweak from there. To catch this event, listen for col component "contactforce" event. For example: entity.col.on("contactforce", this.myCallback, this);

sectionsCount.title: Sections Count
sectionsCount.description: Amount of new sections to create, as well as old sections to destroy.

keepCount.title: Keep Count
keepCount.description: Amount of sections to remain. For example, 2 - would mean destroy [Sections Count] of old sections, keep the current 2, then add [Sections Count] of new sections. This prevents the ground from disappearing under the vehicle.

distance.title: Distance
distance.description: Distance to the end of the road, when reached would trigger new sections generation.

minScreenPos.title: Min Position of Touch to allow joystick
minScreenPos.description: Min Position of Touch to allow joystick. -1 to avoid/

maxScreenPos.title: Max Screen Position
maxScreenPos.description: Max Position of Touch to allow joystick. -1 to avoid

limitPosition.title: Limit Position
limitPosition.description: If we should limit the use of the joystick in a section of the screen

id.title: ID
id.description: A unique ID that would be used to fire an app event when a new value is submitted. If non is provided the entity GUID will be used. The event signature is 'AphroditeTextInput:[ID]:value' with one argument containg the submitted value.

placeholder.title: Placeholder
placeholder.description: A placeholder text to be displayed when no value has been inputted.

type.description: The type of the input field.

maxLength.title: Max Length
maxLength.description: Max number of characters allowed. Type 0 for unlimited characters.

randomDistFactor.description: Randomize distance between items, 0 = no randomization, 1 = randomize to full slot size

randomFlip.title: randomFlip
randomFlip.description: if enabled, the segment will randomly rotate Y to 180 degrees

frustumCulling.title: Frustum Culling
frustumCulling.description: Controls the culling of instances against the camera frustum (frustum culling needs to enabled on each camera component). If false all instances will be rendered regardless of their visibility. Changing this setting requires application reload.

autoUpdate.title: Auto Update
autoUpdate.description: Run the instancer update method automatically per frame. If Frustum Culling is selected this property doesn't have any effect.

cloneMaterials.title: Clone Materials
cloneMaterials.description: If selected all instances will use a clone of the original model material. This is useful when the original material is being used in non instanced models and otherwise it will produce render artifacts. Changing this setting requires application reload.

disableShadows.title: Disable Shadows
disableShadows.description: If selected no shadows buffers will be created (optimization). Requires app reload.

disableTransparent.title: Disable Transparent
disableTransparent.description: If selected transparent mesh instances will not be instanced.

excludeTag.title: Exclude Tag
excludeTag.description: The tag that can be used on entities to exclude them from instancing.

excludeLayers.title: Exclude Layers
excludeLayers.description: Mesh instances rendered in these layers won't be instanced.

camera.title: Camera (Optional)
camera.description:
The camera object to apply bloom effect to. If no camera is provided the script tries
    to use camera component on its current entity. Eventually if no camera is found there as well -
    the first camera in pc.app.systems.camera.cameras is used.

blendmode.title: Blend Mode
blendmode.description:
Bloom blending mode. [Add] is using standard additive mixing, [Screen] results in higher
    contrast in extreme cases like super bright lights, maxed out iterations and low mip limit.

iterations.title: Iterations
iterations.description:
Richness of bloom effect. The difference between 1 and 12 in terms of performance is
    truly negligible so it's recommended to leave it at maximum unless you're targeting specific artistic
    look. Not all iterations may be used internally since downscaling stops at Mip Limit resolution. Low
    and medium number of iterations may produce different results on retina and non-retina displays
    (pc.app.graphicsDevice.maxPixelRatio = 2 or 1).

strength.title: Strength
strength.description: Blending factor. High values together with bright lights result in a steam room look! :D

miplimit.title: Mip Limit
miplimit.description:
This parameter controls the depth of the mip chain by limiting the lowest resolution
    allowed during downscaling. Going below 4 with maxed out iterations may result in a beautiful full
    screen glow which is possible only at sufficiently high resolutions (1024 and up at pixel ratio 1).

thresholdA.title: Threshold A
thresholdA.description:
Thresholding function lower limit. Pixels dimmer than A do not contribute to bloom,
    pixels brighter than B contribute fully, pixels in (A, B) range contribute with smoothstep curve.

thresholdB.title: Threshold B
thresholdB.description:
Thresholding function upper limit. Pixels dimmer than A do not contribute to bloom,
    pixels brighter than B contribute fully, pixels in (A, B) range contribute with smoothstep curve.

radius.title: Filter Radius
radius.description:
Radius of additional blur applied during upsampling stage. It's mostly used to
    dilute a minor moire artefact that is visible at radius (0, 0). Due to the nature of filtering
    Filter Radius may produce slightly different bloom shape depending on device pixel ratio
    (i.e. retina and non-retina displays), so you may want to adjust it dynamically depending on
    window.devicePixelRatio or pc.app.graphicsDevice.maxPixelRatio.

hdrformat.title: HDR Format
hdrformat.description:
Preferred HDR format. Actual format chosen by system may differ due to hardware
    compatibility. 11 bit is the best choice overall, it provides tangible performance benefits and
    is also widely supported even on old devices like iPhone 8.
